Predicting SAT Scores Based on Socioeconomic Factors and Past Grades¶

Sydney Feldman and Gracie Dunaway

Project Website

Project Goals¶

The goal of our project is to answer the question: What are the factors that contribute to a state’s average SAT score? In our first milestone, we began to explore what the effect of family household income had on the average SAT score of students in the US. In this milestone, we want to look deeper into what the differences between the states were, instead of the country’s scores averaged as a whole.

Project Dataset¶

The dataset we have decided to use is called US School Scores, which was found on Kaggle. This data set has 99 columns of information regarding SAT scores by state and US territory from 2005-2015. Although all the information in this dataset is based on when the SAT was out of 2400 points instead of the current 1600 points, it is still relevant to our goals. The only difference between the two tests is that the written portion became optional but the data set we have does not include the writing section so the score is out of 1600 still.

The columns cover a range of topics including scores from different sections of the SAT, subject specific GPA, the average scores based on family income, and many more data points.

You can find the dataset used here.

Collaboration Plan¶

Our collaboration plan is based on an in person meeting every two weeks. During those meeting times, we will discuss our previous work, making sure that it aligns with our goals and that we are on track with time. In addition, we will write out a plan on a shared Google Doc with our expectation and plan for the next two weeks. If we run into any issues, we will schedule time to meet more often, either in person or on Zoom.

Household Income and SAT Scores¶

One of our original hypotheses was that family income has a positive correlation with SAT scores, meaning the higher the family income, the higher the average SAT score. We decided to average the math and reading scores, as we want to look at overall scores for this analysis.

The first table we created includes all the data about how SAT scores relate to family income. We have also added new columns to show the percentage of test-takers in each family income bracket of the total number of test takers in each row. We have also found a total number of test takers.

We tidied this data by removing the state abbreviation column, as it is redundant here, in addition to changing column names to better reflect the data it holds.

This dataset enables us to explore the correlation between income and SAT scores across different states. We can also analyze SAT score trends over the years to determine if there has been an increase in scores over time. Once we establish the correlation between SAT scores and income by state, we can further assess the percentage of people from various income brackets residing in each state to assess the potential impact of regional differences on educational outcomes.

Analysis 1¶

We first want to analyze whether family income has an effect on SAT scores. To start off our analysis, we will create a line graph comparing family income to average SAT score. We decided to take the average of math average score and reading average score

def get_correlation(df_income, statename):
  df_state = df_income[(df_income['State'] == statename)]
  income_columns = []

  df_avg_0k = (df_state['Family Income < 20k: Math Average Score'].mean() + df_state['Family Income < 20k: Reading Average Score'].mean()) / 2
  df_avg_20k = (df_state['Family Income 20-40k: Math Average Score'].mean() + df_state['Family Income 20-40k: Reading Average Score'].mean()) / 2
  df_avg_40k = (df_state['Family Income 40-60k: Math Average Score'].mean() + df_state['Family Income 40-60k: Reading Average Score'].mean()) / 2
  df_avg_60k = (df_state['Family Income 60-80k: Math Average Score'].mean() + df_state['Family Income 60-80k: Reading Average Score'].mean()) / 2
  df_avg_80k = (df_state['Family Income 80-100k: Math Average Score'].mean() + df_state['Family Income 80-100k: Reading Average Score'].mean()) / 2
  df_avg_100k = (df_state['Family Income > 100k: Math Average Score'].mean() + df_state['Family Income > 100k: Reading Average Score'].mean()) / 2
  df_avg = {'score': [df_avg_0k, df_avg_20k, df_avg_40k, df_avg_60k, df_avg_80k, df_avg_100k],
        'income': ['< 20k', '20-40k', '40-60k','60-80k', '80-100k','> 100k'],
            'index': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]}
  df_avg = pd.DataFrame(df_avg)
  correlation_matrix = df_avg.corr()
  r_value = correlation_matrix.loc['score', 'index']

# Extract the correlation coefficient between two specific columns (e.g., Column1 and Column2)
  return r_value

state_correlations = {}

def get_state_plot(df_income_state_0k, df_income_state_20k, df_income_state_40k, df_income_state_60k, df_income_state_80k, df_income_state_100k, statename):
  df_alabama_0k = df_income_state_0k[(df_income_state_0k['State'] == statename)]
  df_alabama_20k = df_income_state_20k[df_income_state_20k['State'] == statename]
  df_alabama_40k = df_income_state_40k[df_income_state_40k['State'] == statename]
  df_alabama_60k = df_income_state_60k[df_income_state_60k['State'] == statename]
  df_alabama_80k = df_income_state_80k[df_income_state_80k['State'] == statename]
  df_alabama_100k = df_income_state_100k[df_income_state_100k['State'] == statename]

  plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
  plot_income_0k = plt.plot(df_alabama_0k['Year'], df_alabama_0k['Avg Score'], label = '<20k')
  plot_income_20k = plt.plot(df_alabama_20k['Year'], df_alabama_20k['Avg Score'], label = '20k-40k')
  plot_income_40k = plt.plot(df_alabama_40k['Year'], df_alabama_40k['Avg Score'], label = '40k-60k')
  plot_income_60k = plt.plot(df_alabama_60k['Year'], df_alabama_60k['Avg Score'], label = '60k-80k')
  plot_income_80k = plt.plot(df_alabama_80k['Year'], df_alabama_80k['Avg Score'], label = '80k-100k')
  plot_income_100k = plt.plot(df_alabama_100k['Year'], df_alabama_100k['Avg Score'], label = '>100k')

  plt.legend()
  plt.xlabel('Year')
  plt.ylabel('Average Score')
  plt.title(f'Average Score Over the Years for Different Income Brackets in {statename}')

GPA by Subjects and SAT scores¶

Another aspect of this data table we want to analyze is the correlation between gpa and SAT test scores. The analysis of this is useful because it can help students predict what they will get on the SAT in each category based on the gpa corresponding with each category. We can also measure academic background and whether the classes a student takes in highschool has any correlation to a student's SAT score

For this analysis we will need to create a separate data table called df_gpa. We will add all of the columns from the original data set that involve gpa and the columns that show the scores between a certain range. We are using the total and not using the gender specific scores since we are not focused on gender for this analysis.

Dataset 2¶

Our secondary data set is also from Kaggle, and contains information organized by state and year, like the first dataset. It contains information about state revenue and spending, the number of students in each grade, 4th and 8th grade standardized test scores, and these separated by factors of race and gender.

We will explore questions about how state revenue effects scores, as well as how previous test scores relate to the same students' SAT scores.

The dataset is linked here

Here we are tidied the data by only including 2005-2015 like the first dataset. We also renamed some columns and entries so that they match the first data set.

8th grade NAEP scores and SAT scores¶

The NAEP or the National Assessment of Educational Progess provide national standardized testing for 4th, 8th, and 12th grade students.

In [ ]:
#notes: need to group all of the 8th grade scores together and then make a graph between the the 8th grade scores and sat scores. probs avg verbal and math together.
# we can also create a model that predicts it and then calculate the accuracy of it
# maybe another bar graph with male and female scores
#question: do socioeconomic factors

The code below shows the process of creating a data frame of 8th grade NAEP exam scores and SAT scores, with a 3 year difference. We chose to look at this 3 year gap because most students take the SAT their junior year of high school, so it is the same group of students taking both exams.

The process of tidying this data and merging these data frames can be done on any set of years with the 3 year difference.

In [43]:
df2_8G = df2[['Year', 'State', 'G08_A_M_READING', 'G08_A_M_MATHEMATICS', 'G08_A_F_READING', 'G08_A_F_MATHEMATICS']]
df2_8G['G08 Average Math'] =(df2_8G['G08_A_M_MATHEMATICS'] + df2_8G['G08_A_F_MATHEMATICS']) / 2
df2_8G['G08 Average Reading'] =(df2_8G['G08_A_M_READING'] + df2_8G['G08_A_F_READING']) / 2
df2_8G = df2_8G.rename(columns = { 'G08_A_M_READING': 'G08 Average Reading Male',
                                  'G08_A_M_MATHEMATICS': 'G08 Average Math Male',
                                   'G08_A_F_MATHEMATICS': 'G08 Average Math Female',
                                   'G08_A_F_READING': 'G08 Average Reading Female'})

df1_scores = df1_scores.rename(columns = {'Total.Math': 'Average Math Score',
                                          'Total.Verbal': 'Average Verbal Score'})



# For Math Scores

df2_8G_2007 = df2_8G[(df2_8G['Year'] == 2007)]
